{
  "text": "U rinary diversion has a history of nearly 150 years, and the ileal conduit previously described by Bricker 1 has long been considered the gold standard for urinary diversion. Orthotopic substitution of the bladder following cystectomy is currently well established. It provides the patient with a superior cosmetic appearance, and the potential for normal voiding function and continence. Despite these advantages, this type of diversion tends to be reserved for selected patients due in part to the perception that the greater technical complexity of orthotoopic urinary diversion leads to greater perioperative and longterm morbidity. This procedure, which reuires a bowel segment, avoids an abdominal stoma and may offer an improved quality of life for patients undergoing radical cystectomy for bladder cancer [CITATION_1] . In 1989, Studer et al. [CITATION_2] described low-pressure bladder substitution using a spherical reservoir consisting of four cross-folded ileal detubularized segments. This neobladder uses an afferent isoperistaltic ileal segment with direct ureteroileal anastomosis, which functions as an antireflex mechanism in order to protect the upper urinary tract. Since 1997, we have adopted the Studer orthotopic bladder substitution following radical cystectomy in 63 male patients with invasive bladder cancer. In the present study, we report our 30 ",
